remixed_from.author: chito
remixed_from.title: CR-10 Heavy Duty customisable modular e3D V6 mount Volcano 5015 ABL

description.text:
Titan aero mount with part cooling fan for the Creality CR-10. You could probably add a bed leveler behind the part fan or attached to it but I don't have one to model.

I also worked up a mount with the extruder stepper at the mounting plate but this lost significantly more bed area. In this orientation you lose about 20mm of bed.

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.2mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

I print the mount upright with supports for the mounting portion, rear lip, and screw holes. You can also print it on its side with the mounting portion on the bed with appropriate supports. I print the fan duct on its side with supports in the fan opening. I also add support under the nozzle's curve on the bed but I suspect these are not neccessary due to the short bridge.

Mount and stepper
Use the two M3 8mm screws that hold the shroud on your existing hotend. You can add another 8mm M3 and a 20mm M3. I used a NEMA 17 Short body stepper from Stepper online which I purchased from Amazon ( http://a.co/5S8RFwi). I probably should have gotten one with the JST PHR-6 on the motor instead of wired. Either way you will need an extension cable or will need to splice extra cable length. If you get the PHR-6, I was unable to find a true M-F extension but I think there are long cables available to run from the system board to the motor. If build your own cable pay attention to the center two wires on the 6 pin side as they cross. If you just splice length, the cross should already be on 6 pin side of the factory cable. I also had to adjust the e-steps (M92 gcode command) to 400 for the stepper I purchased.

Fan V2
I purchased a 12v radial cooling fan from amazon (http://a.co/4eHIuwR). To assemble, you will need 25mm M3 or M4 bolt with nut and two 5-8mm M3 screws and nuts. Loosely install the fan using the M3 screws by placing the nuts in the channel and passing the screws toward the fan - this is opposite of my original plan but works well. Place the M4 screw on the titan side of the fan and work the fan into the mount. If you left slack in the two M3 screws this should be easily done. Tighten the 5mm screws. Alternatively, you could cut about 3mm from the bolt and then pass through the mount towards the fan. I left mine long for now necessitating the reverse setup as shown in the picture.

Fan V1
If you prefer the fan mount outlet to be closer to the nozzle, try the V1 fan mount. I purchased a 12v radial cooling fan from amazon (http://a.co/4eHIuwR). I used a sheet metal screw through the fan mounting hole to retain the fan. It was one I had lying around but I think it was a US #8. It was smaller than the mounting hole on the fan and threads into the mounting bracket. This was really a bug in the design as I intended an M3 screw but the fan abuts the tension adjusting screw and this seems to work fine.

Miscellaneous
I created a replacement cable for the stock hotend using a 9-pin panel mount connector I got at my local electronics shop. I think these are GX-16 connectors. From this I made a short pig-tail that I terminate with JST 2.5mm connectors for the fans and a molex 2 pin for the heater. I then take all of the hotend wiring to the pigtail. If you want to swap back to the stock hot end or if you want to experiment with other hotends this may be the way to go.

There are 3 connectors on the external driver, 1 for the motor, one for power (5v, gnd, gnd, 9-32v), and the last one contains the Step, Dir, Enable plins.

once that is done you just tie the Enable, Step, Dir pins on the external driver to the Step, Dir, Enable of the board or if you need more than what is on your control board you tie them into any 3 free pins and assign them in the firmware.

These micro multicopter frames are designed to not only look amazing, but to provide a strong and lightweight frame. The arms are interchangeable and easily replaceable between frames. Each motor is sunk into the arms in order to reduce vibrations and provide for a much cleaner looking mount. The spider quad frame can be used for fpv with a micro camera. Approximate Weights:
QuadX = 54g
SpiderQuadX = 66g
HexaX = 81g I have not yet received my 3D printer, so this design remains untested. More information and build logs:
www.polakiumengineering.com

The primary components are as follows (available from Hobbyking):
  • Turnigy 1811 2900KV Brushless Outrunner
  • Turnigy Plush 6A ESCs
  • 5030 Props
  • 5030R Props
  • 1000mAh 2S LiPo (Quad) or 2200mAh 2S LiPo (Hex)
  • KK2 Flight Controller or similar (45mm hole spacing, flat side forward)
    • Each arm is secured to the frame with 3x 3mm plastic cable ties. The stock Turnigy motor mounts are removed by unscrewing the two grub screws. A small amount of CA glue is applied mid-way up the base of the motor (away from any moving parts) and the motor is then press fit into the end of each arm. title: Ikea Koppla Power Strip Mounting Brackets (US)

description.text:
This is a really quick design for clip-on brackets for the Ikea Koppla Power Strip (US version) so I could attach it to my Lack table 3d-printer cabinet. The design of the brackets make the entire power strip sit flush with the surface the strip is mounted to so the clips need to be on the outlet side.

The specific strip can be found here: http://www.ikea.com/us/en/catalog/products/70086401/ (700.864.01).

I designed it in Tinkercad using a basic box representing the strip. I did engineer the clip-on parts to have a slight edge to snap into the lines on each side of the strip.

I got the screws as close as flush as I could, using #10 x 3/4 in flat head wood screws I had lying around from home depot.

This is a very tight fit! Which is good as it will not slide around, however be careful installing it as the pointed parts could be sharp. These clips will snap into place when the fit is correct.

This is based on my Cura settings and screws of course so I hope others get this very pleasant snapping experience as well!

As a bonus, I was pleasantly surprised to find out that my Raspberry Pi adapter fit snugly between the clips (last picture).

Thingiverse customizer will not let you import STL files to OpenSCAD script due to arbitrary limitations (see customizer.makerbot.com/docs#limitations). So I wrote simple script that automates the conversion - off2polyhedron.sh. Works as follows:

  • get your STL file and open it in OpenSCAD
  • select File > Export > Export to OFF...
  • run my script on the OFF file
    • e.g. ./off2polyhedron.sh model.off > model.scad
  • the SCAD file is clean OpenSCAD code and can be used as is or copy-pasted to another SCAD file

I'm surprised there do not seem to be any cases for Trackr devices on Thingiverse yet. I just got a bunch of them for family and friends and decided that I'd like a little extra protection for them (and I just started 2-color printing and thought this would be a fun thing to design).

For me, the top and bottom fit extraordinarily well together with simple friction (I gave 0.2mm gap between fitted faces) so I did not design a catch or anything to keep them together (YMMV).

The SketchUp file is included for anyone wishing to customize. The original top and bottom are labeled along with the design and intermediate steps of combining the design with the top to form the new pieces needed for 2-color printing with Cura. Cura needs the bottom piece as one file and separate files for each of the two colors for the top part. One can then pick the source material for each component and then merge the two for printing.

title: MK2 Clone r1 - Prusa i3 style complete 3D Printer

description.text:
Complete set of STL files required to make a MK2 Clone 3D Printer - revision 1 (r1).

Overall cost of build: ~200 USD + cost of printed parts.
The cost can be higher if you will use more expensive parts, eg: stepsticks (TMC2100/TMC2208 instead of A4988), hotend (Original E3Dv6 instead of chinese one), etc.

Frame can be cutted from (at least) 9mm thick plywood or 6mm aluminium (far more expensive, but increases rigidity)

After many tests, I figured out that the printer can easily print with same speeds as Original Prusa MK2s. Linear Advance is already for long time available in Marlin, so there is no problem printing 100mm/s and even more (the speed will be most likely limited by maximum extrusion rate of your hotend). The printing profile available in Slic3r Prusa Edition can be applied just as it to this printer. The only thing needed is adding the MK2Clone printer to Slic3r - setting bed size and proper retraction. If you like to experiment then you can go ahead and increase the accelerations, and max speeds.

Printer is designed to be built from items generally available, while the Original Prusa i3 are using elements made by Prusa Research which are not available to people who don't have the Original one.
All the parts can be easily found on internet market, eg. chinese auctions or ebay.
I strongly recommend to buy all metal parts from local stores, mostly those can be found cheaper than on auctions.

This printer isn't as P&P as the Original one, but it's pretty close. While building this printer you can just open the instructions from prusa manuals, and follow them.

In case of any question feel free to ask in comments, or by website mentioned below.

Whole story about the printer, the build log, and more:
https://prusaclone.wordpress.com/

MK2Clone r1 on github:
https://github.com/q3ok/Prusa-i3-MK2-Clone/tree/r1/

Bill of materials (vitamin description):
https://prusaclone.wordpress.com/bill-of-materials/

For even more rigidity you can mix this MK2 Clone with the 3030 Haribo edition or with a Bear mod, but this will make the printer far more expensive.

description.text: Generic mounts for the edge of cubicle panels. One left and one right side mount. The small pieces are to be attached to the objects you wish to mount. One has holes for screws, the other is intended to be added to a 3d model before printing.

Hi,

description.text:
The Z-axis of the K8400 has no rigid reference.
The entire platform rests upon a flex coupling.
This is unfortunate from out of more resons than I am willing to bore you with.

This modification transform the Z-axis from being referenced by random and pure luck, to being rock steady.

You can see the result in the below Youtube video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wrLdwmv8V64
(Ads are enabled only beacuse Youtube tend to show such search results first.)

I have used this modification for two years now, but thought I lost the files before I could upload them.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Notes:

Note: All .stl are in mm, and need to be scaled down to 1/10.

What you need to print:

  • Two Tr8x1.5 mm nuts.
  • One Upper bearing holder.
  • One Upper bearing holder Cap.
  • One Z-motor bearing mount.

Printing:
The two nuts are the trickiest parts to print, so begin with them, and make sure that they fit the z-axis thread before you move on to printing the next part.

For the nuts:

  • Use your favourite filament.
  • Make sure that your bed is calibrated.
  • Print at the highest resolution.
  • Don't use excessive infill. 20 - 40 % should do.
  • Do not use a setting with extra filament feed added for the first layer.
  • Do not use a setting with extra filament feed added at all.
  • Make sure that the perimeters are printed first.
  • If at first you don't succeed, just move the print to another part of the bed and try again.
  • Set printing speed to slow.
  • As always, avoid changing multiple parameters at the same time.

For other parts:

  • Lower resolutions may be used.
  • For the sturdiest result, use a high amount of infill. 50 - 70%.

Instructions

Warning: All work is done at your own risk. Be careful!

What you need to acquire:

  • Two 8mm bearings. I would suggest using Abec-5 or higher.
  • Eight flat head M3 x 12 mm screws.
  • Four M3 lock nuts.
  • Two M4 x 20 mm insex screws.
  • Two M4 lock nuts.
  • A meticulous mind. (May be abandoned afterwards.)

What may be considered while you're at it:

  • A better flexible coupling than the original one.
  • Buying the two Tr8x1.5 mm nuts if available. (Although the plastic ones work just fine, they're, well, made out of plastics.)

General mounting instructions:

  1. Unplugg all cables to the printer!
  2. Do not overtighten anything! It's just plastics.
  3. Loosen or remove anything that needs to be loosened or removed. Don't attempt to bend or force stuff in place.
  4. Secure the print bed with clamps and/or straps. You don’t want it to fall, breaking things.
  5. Make sure not to damage the flex coupling. Put no load to it.
  6. Carefully put everything where it should be. Look at the picture and figure it out. I may come up with a more detailed instruction later on, but don't count on it.
  7. Put special attention to that the flex coupling shall be unloaded. The bed shall rest upon the Upper bearing holder assembly only. The flex coupling shall neither push, nor pull the threaded rod.

General adjustment instructions:
First thing to know about parallel rods: There are no parallel rods, you simply have to make them parallel enough...

  1. Loosen the upper rod clamps. Position the bed in the upper position, and slightly retighten the rod clamps.
  2. Loosen the mounting screws of the beige plastic bed thread, and slightly retighten.
  3. Loosen the stepper motor mount.
  4. Loosen the lower rod clamps. Position the bed in the lower position, and slightly retighten the rod clamps.
  5. Loosen the mounting screws of the beige plastic bed thread, and slightly retighten.
  6. Retighten the stepper motor mount
  7. Repeat from 1. until the bed and screw runs smoothly along the entire print height.
  8. Tighten all screws, but not the plastic Tr8x1.5 nuts.
  9. Adjust by using the nuts until the flex coupling is completely unloaded. .
  10. When so, tighten both nuts towards the upper bearing, thus locking each other.

description.text:
Disclaimer: I AM NOT a luthier (craftsperson who makes and repairs stringed instruments) and this is probably NOT a very good repair. If your ukelele breaks, talk to somebody who knows about fixing instruments, not a computer scientist who has a uke and a 3D printer.

I have a ukelele with probably little monetary value, but sentimental value and practical value to me. It's probably on the high-end of "souvenir ukes", in that it's really rather playable (as far as I know, which isn't much), but has "Hawaii" printed on it along with some wooden dolphin cutouts glued on the body, and fishing line around some of the tuners to use to hang/display it. A piece broke, and this is the replacement piece I printed to keep it playable longer.

This "thing" may also serve as a reasonable introduction to some basic OpenSCAD concepts, since the .scad file is heavily documented, both for easy customization, as well as for instruction.

On this particular uke of mine are what are known as "friction tuners" for the strings: there's a tuning key for each string that just goes straight through to the front of the uke head directly turning, to tighten and loosen each string, no gears involved. All that holds the tune with these particular tuners is the friction between a slope on the base of the plastic tuning key/knob and a rather special-looking (and I'd guess nylon) washer sandwiched between that key and the back of the headstock. That washer on one of the tuners (G, not surprising to me since I had the hardest time keeping that string in tune) just cracked into two pieces, so I measured a combination of the key surface that was now easily accessible, and the other washers still intact, to design a quick and easy printed replacement.

So here it is - the replacement part I needed for my friction tuner.

Note: After looking around at search results for "uke friction tuners" it does appear that there are a wide variety of designs, and thus the highly adventurous could probably use this as a starting point to re-design/replace both of the plastic parts of the tuner, to potentially provide a nicer tuning experience.

Updated to have a better "Customizer" experience. Still probably easiest to download and edit locally, but now I even have parameter validation in the customizer.

Notes:

I printed this in ABS (blue Octave 1.75mm, if you're curious), because that's what I have/can print. Not sure the importance of the material here, other than that I think the original was nylon or at least that nylon seems like it would have been the "ideal" thing, if fully smooth.

One semi-important note: to avoid a "ridge" in the resulting print, make sure that "Fixed shell starting point" is unchecked (or the equivalent in your slicer if you use something other than MakerBot Desktop). If you let it start all the shells at the same angular position, you'll get a ridge on that inside "bearing" surface, instead of some very small randomly-distributed bumps. I suspect, but did not test, that having a ridge might "feel weird" or wear the tuner down in an undesired way.

If you can get away with not using a raft, or maybe just using a brim (presumably depends on your printer and material), that would be ideal, since on these little parts it can be hard to remove the raft sometimes, especially if your nozzle-buildplate spacing isn't perfect. (I can only remove the raft if I print with my right extruder, not my left, for example)

It would probably be nicer, and smoother, with a smaller layer height.

I set the infill fairly high because this is a small part that will bear some degree of compressive load. Might be unnecessary, you're welcome to experiment.

Remove raft, smooth bottom

If you had to use a raft, remove it. Same for a brim.

If the bottom isn't nice and smooth, you probably want to sand it, or at least file it. (This is the part that will be against the headstock of the uke.)

If you have a way, you can try smoothing the inside bearing surface a bit. It's an awkward shape to sand, though, so I didn't, and it still works fine for me.

Remove tuner screw and install

Unscrew the screw that tightens/loosens the tuner's tension (not the tuner itself - you can probably leave that mostly fully wound) so you can slide the key off the peg. Then, slide your new washer in place (I'm assuming your old one broke away like mine) then put the key back on. Tighten screw to personal preference and tune your uke!

I made this with OpenSCAD, and have included a very-highly-commented source file so that you can "make one to order" custom for your needs - since I have no idea how common the particular model of tuner I have is.

You can use the "Customizer" on the Thingiverse web site, but note that it actually doesn't show the entire comment for each variable (and some of them you don't need to edit), and I don't think I can customize the customizer, so it might be easier to just do it in text on your own machine if possible.

When measuring, it may help to refer to the OpenSCAD preview, a capture of which I've included in this "thing" - the shape consists of a truncated cone (the yellow solid) with a smaller, "upside-down" truncated cone, and a cylinder, subtracted from it (the green inner surfaces). You can make all the measurements required from just the key on the broken tuner, as well as the outside of one intact washer: shouldn't need to remove an intact washer to measure.

You can see an original washer in one of the pictures I uploaded, on an adjacent tuner to the one with the printed tuner.

I am NOT a luthier (craftsperson who makes and repairs stringed instruments) and this is probably NOT a very good repair. If your ukelele breaks, talk to somebody who knows about fixing instruments, not a computer scientist who has a uke and a 3D printer. I have no idea if this will damage your uke, cause your cat to start plotting revenge against you, etc.

As they say, "for novelty purposes only". (That said, if your needs are similar to mine and you find this suitable, I'd love to see your "make" of it!)

description.text:
For some time I have wanted to have a large scale LED based clock, this is the result. Using these files each digit is almost 11" in height. I used a strip of 30 LED's per meter and each segment has 3 LED's in it, while the colon segments house a single LED. An Arduino Nano runs the whole thing along with a DS1307 chip to keep accurate time - even when it is turned off.

There are three buttons. When the clock is running the hour and minute buttons will change the colour. The setting button, pressed briefly will change the colon colour.

The clock can have different colours for the hours, minutes and colon, you can pick from red, orange, yellow, green, cyan, blue, purple, magenta, "harlequin", colour fade and white. The harlequin is where each segment is a different colour and fades across the rainbow. colour fade will fade the whole digit through the rainbow.

If you press the setting button down for 2 seconds the clock will go into a setting mode, allowing the changing of the time (press and hold the hour/minute buttons to change the time). The setting button can be briefly pressed to turn DST on and off and held for 2 seconds to set the time and switch back to time display.

I am still working on this. Also my programming skills are self taught and may not be the most efficient methods! It also needs a number of support libraries, check the #include lines for which ones.

description.text:
With this model I've taken my original infinity cube design and attempted to make it a small as possible. At only 2cm or 0.8" when folded, this one takes less than an hour to print!

The inspiration for this was the truly awesome Tiny Excavator - and it's cousins - by the talented Stian Ervik Wahlvaag.

I was impressed at how small my printer could go with regards making small in-print moving parts, and having proved that larger joints work on the regular cube, I set about making one as small as I dare.

https://youtu.be/LRBL6jsaNY0

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 Plus

Rafts:

No

No

0.2mm

40%

Notes:

Material - PLA, 1.75mm
Extruder: 0.4mm
Extruder Temp: 200
Bed Temp: 50
Print Speed: 45mm/s
Flow: 90%

On this tiny version of the infinity cube, there's a lot of fusing of parts going on.

The best advice I can give is, trim any excess brim if there is any, and gently but firmly try to flex the hinges on their axis. If you get one pair free, don't be tempted to use the cubes as leverage as you might break the hinge walls - try to swing the small cube around the axis of the hinge. It's doable with a bit of effort.

Update: I have added separate hinge and cube STL files - you may be able to use these to print a dual colour infinity cube, however I can't get my Cura to overlap the files so I have no idea how this would work in practice

The main obstacles in making this so tiny are 1/ the fragility of PLA at small scales and 2/ the accuracy of the printer when making lots of small movements.

So when dealing with 1/ above, my first problem was that the joints would break through the walls of the cube when flexed - the PLA was just too thin. On the pictured cube, I increased the thickness of the hole to the wall of the cube by 0.1mm, keeping the outer radii the same. To maintain the small tolerances, this meant that the pins on the hinge had to be made smaller also. I also made the pins 0.1mm shorter to give the walls of the holes a tiny bit of added strength.

There's not much you can do about 2/ other than to slow down the print speed and flow. For the cube pictured, I maintained the 45mm/s - 90% settings I had used on the larger cube.

Nun ja, hiermit gibt euer FAN0 Port also sprich der Teilekühler 12 Volt ±0,2V aus anstatt max 9 Volt.
